"""
mkt-context | Leviticus | chapters 16–18
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-leviticus-16-18-fill.py

Ch 16: Yom Kippur — the two-goat mechanism, Azazel crux, the linen-only vestments,
        concentric blood-manipulation sequence in the most holy place;
        ch 16 v1 already present.
Ch 17: Blood and sanctuary centralization — prohibition on field-slaughter to
        se'irim; blood-is-nefesh theology; game-blood covering; terefah impurity.
Ch 18: Sexual prohibitions framed by Egypt/Canaan contrast; ervah-pattern;
        Molech in a sex-law chapter; land-vomiting metaphor.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DATA = {
  "16": {
    "2": "<p>YHWH said to Moses: Tell Aaron your brother not to come at any time into the Holy Place inside the veil, before the mercy seat that is on the ark, so that he may not die — the death-threat prohibition establishes that the most holy place is inaccessible except under the precisely controlled conditions of Yom Kippur. The restriction is specifically Aaronic (not just priestly): only the high priest may enter, and only on one day per year. In Egyptian temple practice, the innermost sanctuary containing the divine image was similarly restricted; only the highest priests (or the Pharaoh in ritual persona) could approach; the similarity in spatial restriction highlights the theological difference — the Israelite prohibition aims at protecting the covenant community from divine judgment, not protecting a divine image from human view.</p>",
    "3": "<p>But in this way Aaron shall come into the Holy Place: with a bull from the herd for a sin offering and a ram for a burnt offering — the high priest enters with specific prescribed animals, not freely. The bull is for Aaron's own atonement (vv.6,11-14) before he can intercede for the congregation; the sequence personal atonement → communal atonement is structurally fundamental to Yom Kippur. No parallel Mesopotamian rite requires the officiating priest to first atone for himself before performing communal atonement; the Levitical insistence on the priest's own sinfulness is theologically distinctive.</p>",
    "4": "<p>He shall put on the holy linen coat and shall have the linen undergarments on his body, and he shall tie the linen sash around his waist, and wear the linen turban; these are the holy garments — Yom Kippur's vestments are strikingly simpler than the regular high-priestly garments (Exod 28: gold, blue, purple, scarlet, precious stones, bells). The linen-only set (without gold or jewels) is the same type worn by ordinary priests; the high priest's self-reduction to ordinary priestly garb for the day's atonement work signals humility and vulnerability before YHWH. Linen is also associated with the resurrection/purity in later theology; its whiteness became the dominant Yom Kippur visual symbol (cf. Isa 1:18).</p>",
    "5": "<p>And he shall take from the congregation of the people of Israel two male goats for a sin offering and one ram for a burnt offering — the two goats for the communal sin offering are the unique feature of Yom Kippur not found elsewhere in Leviticus or the ANE sacrificial corpus; both goats constitute a single sin offering (cf. v.5: 'two male goats for a sin offering'), but their respective fates divide: one dies as a chatat, one is sent alive to Azazel.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Aaron shall offer the bull as a sin offering for himself and shall make atonement for himself and for his house — the bull sin offering for Aaron and his household precedes the communal goat sin offering; the high priest's personal atonement is a prerequisite for his capacity to atone for others. This structural requirement — the priest must be atoned for before he can atone on behalf of others — is emphasized in the Yom Kippur rubric and later in Heb 7:27 as a limitation that the perfect High Priest transcends.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Then he shall take the two goats and set them before YHWH at the entrance of the tent of meeting — the two-goat presentation before YHWH at the sanctuary entrance establishes that both goats are simultaneously offered as a single complex offering; neither is simply a random animal from the flock but a paired sacrificial unit whose fate is determined by lot (v.8). The lot-casting gives the selection divine rather than human determination.</p>",
    "8": "<p>And Aaron shall cast lots over the two goats, one lot for YHWH and one lot for Azazel (<em>goral echad la-YHWH vegoral echad la-Azazel</em>) — the Azazel lot is one of the most debated cruxes in Leviticus. Three main interpretive streams: (1) <em>Azazel</em> as a place name (a rocky/remote place — related to <em>ez</em> goat + <em>azal</em> remove/disappear, 'the goat of removal'); (2) a personal/demonic name for a wilderness spirit — supported by 1 Enoch 8 and 10, which describe Azazel as a fallen angel; (3) a descriptor meaning 'complete sending-away.' The parallel structure <em>la-YHWH/la-Azazel</em> suggests Azazel is a personal entity parallel to YHWH, which has led most modern scholars to accept the demonic-entity interpretation — the goat is sent back to the demonic source of disorder in the wilderness, not sacrificed to it.</p>",
    "9": "<p>And Aaron shall present the goat on which the lot fell for YHWH and use it as a sin offering — the YHWH-lot goat follows the standard chatat procedure: slaughter, blood manipulation on the kapporet, tent of meeting, and outer altar. Its function is the ritual purification of the sanctuary from the accumulated impurities of the year.</p>",
    "10": "<p>But the goat on which the lot fell for Azazel shall be presented alive before YHWH to make atonement over it, that it may be sent away into the wilderness to Azazel — the Azazel-goat is not slaughtered; it is presented alive before YHWH for the confession-and-laying-on-of-hands rite (vv.21-22) and then sent alive into the wilderness. The pairing of a slaughtered goat (sanctuary purification) and a released goat (sin-removal from the community) creates a comprehensive atonement that addresses both the sanctuary's defilement and the people's accumulated guilt.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Aaron shall present the bull as a sin offering for himself, and shall make atonement for himself and for his house. He shall kill the bull as a sin offering for himself — the second mention of the bull sin offering for Aaron; the repetition reinforces the structural priority of the high priest's own atonement. The bull blood will be brought inside the veil (v.14) in the same procedure as the goat blood (v.15), providing full atonement coverage for both priest and congregation.</p>",
    "12": "<p>And he shall take a censer full of coals of fire from the altar before YHWH, and two handfuls of sweet incense beaten small, and he shall bring it inside the veil — the incense screen is the high priest's protection in the most holy place: the incense cloud covers the kapporet (mercy seat) so that Aaron does not see it directly and die (v.13). In Mesopotamian ritual, priests carried incense as part of divine approach protocols — the incense as divine encounter protection is a shared ANE ritual element, but the Levitical specification that it protects the officiating priest from the divine presence above the ark is distinctive.</p>",
    "13": "<p>And he shall put the incense on the fire before YHWH, that the cloud of the incense may cover the mercy seat that is over the testimony, so that he does not die — the kapporet (mercy seat, or atonement-cover) is the golden lid of the ark of the covenant, flanked by the cherubim (Exod 25:17-22). YHWH speaks from between the cherubim (Exod 25:22); the incense cloud interposes between the high priest and this most direct divine manifestation point. The protective incense protocol implies that even the high priest, performing the most sacred act of the liturgical year, approaches YHWH under a kind of protective mediation.</p>",
    "14": "<p>And he shall take some of the blood of the bull and sprinkle it with his finger on the front of the mercy seat on the east side, and in front of the mercy seat he shall sprinkle the blood with his finger seven times — the blood manipulation on the kapporet proceeds in two stages: one application on the front east face, then seven sprinklings in front of the kapporet (downward, toward the floor or the front of the ark). The number seven (completeness) recurs throughout Levitical blood rituals; here it covers the full spatial surface of the most holy place with atoning blood.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Then he shall kill the goat of the sin offering that is for the people and bring its blood inside the veil and do with its blood as he did with the blood of the bull, sprinkling it over the mercy seat and in front of the mercy seat — the people's sin offering goat receives identical blood manipulation to the priest's bull; the spatial procedure in the most holy place is the same for both, ensuring comprehensive atonement coverage for priest and people alike. The double entry into the most holy place (for bull blood, then for goat blood) required two separate entries through the veil.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Thus he shall make atonement for the Holy Place, because of the uncleannesses of the people of Israel and because of their transgressions, all their sins — the explicit statement that the sanctuary itself requires atonement: the accumulated impurities and sins of the people throughout the year have penetrated and defiled even the most holy place. This understanding that sin defiles the sanctuary (rather than only the sinner) is a distinctive Levitical concept; the sanctuary must be periodically purified of this accumulated contamination, not merely the individual worshipers.</p>",
    "17": "<p>No one may be in the tent of meeting from the time he enters to make atonement in the Holy Place until he comes out and has made atonement for himself and for his house and for all the assembly of Israel — the total exclusion of all other persons from the tent of meeting during the high priest's entry into the most holy place creates the maximum possible sacral isolation. The high priest stands utterly alone before YHWH during the most critical moment of the liturgical year.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Then he shall go out to the altar that is before YHWH and make atonement for it, and shall take some of the blood of the bull and some of the blood of the goat, and put it on the horns of the altar all around — after the inner sanctuary's atonement, the outer altar receives blood from both the bull and the goat. The mixed blood (from both the priestly and communal offerings) applied to the outer altar ensures that this most publicly visible locus of worship is also covered by the day's atonement.</p>",
    "19": "<p>And he shall sprinkle some of the blood on it with his finger seven times, and cleanse it and consecrate it from the uncleannesses of the people of Israel — seven sprinklings on the outer altar (as on the kapporet) complete the purification cycle; <em>ve-qiddesho</em> (consecrate it, reconsecrate it) indicates that the altar's holiness has been compromised by the year's accumulated defilements and is now restored. The Yom Kippur procedure thus resets the entire sanctuary complex to its original consecrated state.</p>",
    "20": "<p>And when he has made an end of atoning for the Holy Place and the tent of meeting and the altar, he shall present the live goat — the sequence is complete: most holy place → tent of meeting → outer altar → now the live Azazel goat. The spatial movement from innermost to outermost mirrors the concentric holiness zones of the tabernacle; atonement proceeds from the most sacred center outward.</p>",
    "21": "<p>And Aaron shall lay both his hands on the head of the live goat and confess over it all the iniquities of the people of Israel, and all their transgressions, all their sins. And he shall put them on the head of the goat and send it away into the wilderness by the hand of a man who is in readiness — the laying of both hands (<em>shtei yadav</em>) on the scapegoat's head is unique in Levitical ritual (other laying-on-of-hand rites use one hand, Lev 1:4); the full weight of priestly identification transfers the entire community's accumulated sin-load to the goat. The verbal confession is the only instance in the sacrificial legislation where the content of the atonement act is explicitly verbal; the comprehensive three-term sin-vocabulary (<em>avonot, pesha'im, chata'ot</em>) covers the full range of Israelite moral failure.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The goat shall bear all their iniquities on itself to a remote area, and he shall let the goat go free in the wilderness — the goat literally carries (<em>nasa</em>) the sins; the verb is the same used for prophetic sin-bearing (Isa 53:4,11,12). The destination is <em>eretz gezeirah</em> (a cut-off land, a remote/separated region), Azazel's domain. Second Temple practice added a rocky precipice (according to Mishnah Yoma 6:6) over which the goat was pushed to prevent its return; the Talmud mentions that a red thread tied to the precipice would turn white as a sign of divine acceptance, echoing Isa 1:18.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Then Aaron shall come into the tent of meeting and shall take off the linen garments that he put on when he went into the Holy Place and shall leave them there — the linen Yom Kippur vestments are left in the tent of meeting after the inner ceremonies; they are not taken out or reused. The spatial containment of the most-holy garments within the tent reflects the principle that what has been in the most holy place remains contaminated with its holiness and cannot return to ordinary use.</p>",
    "24": "<p>And he shall bathe his body in water in a holy place and put on his garments and come out and offer his burnt offering and the burnt offering of the people and make atonement for himself and for the people — the post-inner-sanctuary procedure: bathing (transition purification from the most holy contact), change to regular high-priestly garments, then burnt offerings. The personal burnt offering reaffirms Aaron's complete consecration after the day's most intimate divine encounter.</p>",
    "25": "<p>And the fat of the sin offering he shall burn on the altar — the fat portions of both sin offering animals (bull and goat) burn on the outer altar as the standard YHWH-portion; even on Yom Kippur the basic sacrificial mechanics remain consistent with the sacrifice laws of Lev 3–7.</p>",
    "26": "<p>And he who lets the goat go to Azazel shall wash his clothes and bathe his body in water, and afterward he may come into the camp — the person who led the Azazel goat to the wilderness contracts impurity from the contact with the sin-laden goat; the same laundering-and-bathing purification required after other impurity contacts (Lev 11:25,28,40; 14:8; 15:5-8) applies here. The impurity transmission confirms that the goat genuinely carried sin, not merely symbolically represented it.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The bull for the sin offering and the goat for the sin offering, whose blood was brought in to make atonement in the Holy Place, shall be carried outside the camp. Their skin and their flesh and their dung shall be burned up with fire — the two sin offering animals whose blood entered the most holy place are burned outside the camp, as with all inward-blood-manipulation sin offerings (Lev 4:12,21; 6:30). The outside-camp burning of the most-holy sin offering animals creates a spatial parallel to the outside-camp destination of the Azazel goat; both forms of sin removal go outside.</p>",
    "28": "<p>And he who burns them shall wash his clothes and bathe his body in water, and afterward he may come into the camp — the person who burns the sin offering carcasses also contracts impurity requiring laundering and bathing. The systematic impurity from contact with sin-laden sacrificial materials reflects the objective weight of the sin these offerings have borne.</p>",
    "29": "<p>And it shall be a statute to you forever that in the seventh month, on the tenth day of the month, you shall afflict yourselves (<em>ve-initem et-nafshoteichem</em>) and shall do no work, either the native or the stranger who sojourns among you — Yom Kippur's two community requirements: self-affliction (<em>innui nefesh</em>, which rabbinic tradition interprets as fasting plus five other abstentions: bathing, anointing, leather shoes, marital relations) and complete work-prohibition. The tenth of the seventh month (Tishri) positions Yom Kippur five days before Sukkoth and ten days after Rosh Hashanah (Feast of Trumpets), creating the 'ten days of awe' structure of the high holy day season in Jewish liturgical calendar.</p>",
    "30": "<p>For on this day shall atonement be made for you to cleanse you. You shall be clean before YHWH from all your sins — the definitive statement of Yom Kippur's scope: <em>mikal chatoteichem lifney YHWH titharu</em> (from all your sins before YHWH you shall be clean). The comprehensive cleansing covers the full year's accumulated sins of the entire community; the day's procedures together accomplish what no individual sacrifice could: a complete annual reset of the covenant relationship.</p>",
    "31": "<p>It is a Sabbath of solemn rest to you (<em>shabbat shabbaton hi lachem</em>), and you shall afflict yourselves; it is a statute forever — the double Sabbath formula <em>shabbat shabbaton</em> (the most intense Sabbath-rest) is used only for Yom Kippur (here and Lev 23:32) and for the Sabbath itself (Exod 31:15; 35:2; Lev 23:3), marking Yom Kippur as the highest-intensity day of rest in the liturgical calendar.</p>",
    "32": "<p>And the priest who is anointed and consecrated to serve as priest in his father's place shall make atonement, wearing the holy linen garments — the provision for successor high priests ensures the Yom Kippur procedure is not dependent on Aaron personally but perpetuates through the Aaronic line; whoever holds the high-priestly office wears the linen garments and performs the prescribed rites. The phrase <em>tachat aviv</em> (in his father's place) establishes the hereditary succession principle for the high priesthood.</p>",
    "33": "<p>He shall make atonement for the holy sanctuary, and he shall make atonement for the tent of meeting and for the altar, and he shall make atonement for the priests and for all the people of the assembly — the four-part atonement summary: sanctuary, tent of meeting, altar, people. The concentric spatial sequence (from innermost sacred to the community) recapitulates the procedural order of vv.14-19. The comprehensive scope — all sacred spaces and all people — confirms that Yom Kippur is a total-reset mechanism for the entire covenantal system.</p>",
    "34": "<p>And this shall be a statute forever for you, that atonement may be made for the people of Israel once in the year because of all their sins. And Moses did as YHWH commanded him — the closing statute-formula (<em>chuqat olam</em>) establishes Yom Kippur as a permanent annual institution; the once-per-year restriction (<em>achat bashanah</em>) is as theologically significant as the comprehensiveness of the atonement. The annual cycle of accumulated sin + annual atonement creates the rhythm of Israelite covenantal life until the once-for-all atonement of Christ (Heb 9:7,12,25-28).</p>"
  },
  "17": {
    "1": "<p>And YHWH spoke to Moses — the new revelation formula opens a new legislative unit; ch 17 addresses the blood-slaughter-centralization laws that bridge the Yom Kippur materials and the Holiness Code proper (chs 17–26). The chapter's concern with blood (vv.3-16) and with the theological basis of the prohibition creates one of the most important theological passages in Leviticus.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Speak to Aaron and his sons and to all the people of Israel and say to them — the expanded address (Aaron, his sons, all Israel) marks this as a comprehensive law applying to all, not only priests; the blood legislation transcends cultic categories and governs the entire community's relationship to blood.</p>",
    "3": "<p>If any one of the house of Israel kills an ox or a lamb or a goat in the camp, or kills it outside the camp — the prohibition covers all slaughter of the three sacrificial species (ox, sheep, goat) both inside and outside the camp. This is the centralization law: all slaughter of these animals must be brought to the sanctuary, not performed in private. The 'outside the camp' specification covers the wilderness context; in the land, the parallel rule will be adapted (Deut 12 permits non-sacrificial slaughter at any location but requires all sacrifice at the central sanctuary).</p>",
    "4": "<p>And does not bring it to the entrance of the tent of meeting to offer it as an offering to YHWH in front of the tabernacle of YHWH, bloodguilt shall be imputed to that man (<em>dam yechashev la-ish ha-hu</em>) — unauthorized slaughter of sacrificial animals incurs bloodguilt (<em>dam</em>) as though the person had shed human blood. The severity of the penalty (karet, v.4b) reflects the theological claim that all slaughter of domestic animals belongs to YHWH's sacrificial economy; private killing outside the sanctuary denies YHWH's ownership of animal life.</p>",
    "5": "<p>This is to the end that the people of Israel may bring their sacrifices that they sacrifice in the open field (<em>al-peney ha-sadeh</em>), that they may bring them to YHWH, to the priest at the entrance of the tent of meeting — the purpose clause: the law drives all field-slaughter into the sanctuary system. The 'open field' sacrifices are the unauthorized alternative that the centralization law prohibits; the phrase implies that pre-centralization or non-Israelite practice involved field slaughter without priestly mediation.</p>",
    "6": "<p>And the priest shall throw the blood on the altar of YHWH at the entrance of the tent of meeting and burn the fat for a pleasing aroma to YHWH — the re-categorized field slaughter becomes a peace offering (shelamim) with standard blood and fat procedures; the formerly unauthorized killing is transformed into legitimate communal worship. This economically validates the centralization law: it is not confiscatory but transformative, integrating all animal slaughter into the covenant fellowship-meal structure.</p>",
    "7": "<p>So they shall no more sacrifice their sacrifices to goat demons (<em>la-se'irim asher hem zonim achareihem</em>), after whom they whore. This shall be a statute forever for them throughout their generations — the se'irim (goat-demons, satyrs) are the wilderness spirit-beings to whom unauthorized field sacrifices were directed; the prostitution language (<em>zonim</em>, whoring) frames these offerings as spiritual adultery. The se'irim appear in Isa 13:21 and 34:14 as wilderness spirits; Lev 17:7's reference implies that such field-sacrifices to goat-demons were an actual practice in Israel's wilderness experience (cf. the golden calf incident, Amos 5:25-26).</p>",
    "8": "<p>And you shall say to them, Any one of the house of Israel, or of the strangers who sojourn among them, who offers a burnt offering or sacrifice — the centralization law extends to sojourning Gentiles residing in Israel; they are equally prohibited from unauthorized sacrifice. The inclusion of the <em>ger</em> (sojourner) in the same legislation as Israel is consistent throughout Lev 17 (vv.10,12,13,15) and reflects the Holiness Code's principle that the land itself requires protection from all defilement, regardless of the offender's ethnic identity.</p>",
    "9": "<p>And does not bring it to the entrance of the tent of meeting to offer it to YHWH, that man shall be cut off from his people — karet for unauthorized sacrifice applies equally to Israelite and sojourner; the sanctity of the centralized sanctuary system is non-negotiable for all who live within the covenant community's territory.</p>",
    "10": "<p>If any one of the house of Israel or of the strangers who sojourn among them eats any blood, I will set my face against that person who eats blood and will cut him off from among his people — the blood-eating prohibition is restated with the divine first-person threat (<em>natati panay</em>, I will set my face against) that signals YHWH's direct punitive action rather than communal execution. The prohibition applies universally; the following verse (v.11) provides the theological rationale.</p>",
    "11": "<p>For the life (<em>nefesh</em>) of the flesh is in the blood, and I have given it for you on the altar to make atonement for your souls, for it is the blood that makes atonement by the life (<em>ki ha-dam hu ba-nefesh yekhapper</em>) — the foundational theological statement of Levitical sacrifice: blood contains/is the nefesh (life/soul) of the flesh; YHWH has given blood specifically for the altar-atonement function; and it is the blood (qua life-substance) that performs atonement. This three-part statement explains why blood is simultaneously the most sacred substance (YHWH's atonement-medium) and the most prohibited food (it belongs to YHWH). The blood-nefesh identification has no parallel in ANE sacrificial theology; Mesopotamian texts describe gods consuming food offerings but do not articulate a blood-as-life-for-atonement theology.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Therefore I have said to the people of Israel, No person among you shall eat blood, neither shall any stranger who sojourns among you eat blood — the deductive conclusion from v.11: because blood is nefesh given for atonement, it may not be eaten. The logical structure (theological premise → behavioral prohibition) is explicit, making Lev 17:11 the most clearly reasoned prohibition in the Levitical law code.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Any one also of the people of Israel, or of the strangers who sojourn among them, who takes in hunting any beast or bird that may be eaten shall pour out its blood and cover it with earth (<em>shefakh dam vekissahu be-afar</em>) — the game-animal blood rule: hunted animals (not sacrificeable) still require blood respect; their blood must be poured out and covered with earth (not swallowed, not left exposed). The earth-covering creates a kind of minimal 'burial' of the life-substance; the action acknowledges that even the life of a wild animal belongs to YHWH and cannot simply be consumed or wasted.</p>",
    "14": "<p>For the life of every creature is its blood: its blood is its life. Therefore I have said to the people of Israel, You shall not eat the blood of any creature, for the life of every creature is its blood. Whoever eats it shall be cut off — the restatement of v.11's principle extended to all creatures (not only domestic sacrificial animals): nefesh-in-blood is universal. The double formulation (<em>ki nefesh kol-basar damo beenafesho hu</em>) and the triple repetition of the nefesh-blood identification within vv.11-14 emphasize that this is the core theological claim of the chapter.</p>",
    "15": "<p>And every person who eats what dies of itself (<em>neveilah</em>) or what is torn by beasts (<em>terefah</em>), whether he is a native or a sojourner, shall wash his clothes and bathe himself in water and be unclean until the evening; then he shall be clean — eating neveilah or terefah creates until-evening impurity (not karet); these animals died without proper blood-drainage through slaughter. The lesser penalty than blood-eating reflects that the prohibition is still operative but the blood has not been deliberately consumed in the same sense as fresh blood eating.</p>",
    "16": "<p>But if he does not wash them or bathe his flesh, he shall bear his iniquity — the penalty for failure to perform the required laundering-and-bathing purification after eating neveilah/terefah; bearing iniquity (<em>avono yissa</em>) is a lesser consequence than karet but still indicates personal culpability for ignoring a known purification requirement.</p>"
  },
  "18": {
    "1": "<p>And YHWH spoke to Moses, saying — the new revelation formula opens the most extensive sexual-ethics legislation in the Torah; Lev 18 is the foundational document of Israelite sexual ethics, framed by the Egypt/Canaan contrast (vv.2-5,24-30) and structured around the <em>ervah</em> (nakedness) motif.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Speak to the people of Israel and say to them, I am YHWH your God — the divine self-identification formula (<em>ani YHWH Eloheichem</em>) grounds the sexual ethics in covenant identity before any specific prohibition; the motivation for the following legislation is not primarily social utility or natural law but covenant loyalty to the one who brought Israel out of Egypt. The Holiness Code (chs 17–26) opens and closes every major section with variations of this formula.</p>",
    "3": "<p>You shall not do as they do in the land of Egypt, where you lived, and you shall not do as they do in the land of Canaan, to which I am bringing you. You shall not walk in their statutes — the negative framing by two geographical-cultural poles: Egypt (the past of slavery) and Canaan (the future of conquest). Both cultures serve as negative examples of sexual practice; the framing of Israelite ethics as a third way between two known systems is structurally similar to the Deuteronomic contrast between Egypt and Canaan (Deut 11:10; 17:16). Egyptian records show no comprehensive sexual prohibition code; Ugaritic texts from Canaan similarly show no equivalent to the Levitical list.</p>",
    "4": "<p>You shall follow my rules and keep my statutes and walk in them. I am YHWH your God — the positive counterpart to v.3's negative: instead of Egyptian/Canaanite statutes, Israel is to follow YHWH's <em>mishpatim</em> (judgments) and <em>chuqqim</em> (statutes). The self-identification formula (<em>ani YHWH Eloheichem</em>) repeated from v.2 creates a bracketing emphasis: the entire legislative section hangs on covenant identity.</p>",
    "5": "<p>You shall therefore keep my statutes and my rules; if a person does them, he shall live by them (<em>va-chai bahem</em>): I am YHWH — the promise of life through the statutes is one of the most important statements in Leviticus; Paul cites it in Gal 3:12 and Rom 10:5 as the principle of the law-covenant (life through doing), which he contrasts with faith-righteousness. Ezekiel 20:11,13,21 also cites this verse as the foundational covenant life-promise.</p>",
    "6": "<p>None of you shall approach any one of his close relatives to uncover nakedness (<em>lo tiqrevu lechol-she'er besaro legalot ervah</em>). I am YHWH — <em>she'er</em> (flesh-kin) covers blood relatives and relatives by marriage; <em>galot ervah</em> (uncover nakedness) is the chapter's central euphemism for sexual intercourse within prohibited relationships. The proximity of kinship is the defining criterion; the <em>ervah</em> framework defines the family as a protected zone of non-sexual relationships.</p>",
    "7": "<p>You shall not uncover the nakedness of your father, which is the nakedness of your mother; she is your mother, you shall not uncover her nakedness — the mother is doubly protected: directly (she is your mother) and indirectly (her sexuality belongs to the father). The equivalence 'father's nakedness = mother's nakedness' (v.8 separates these for the stepmother case) indicates that the first prohibition covers the biological mother primarily as the father's wife.</p>",
    "8": "<p>You shall not uncover the nakedness of your father's wife; it is your father's nakedness — the stepmother case (father's wife who is not biological mother): the prohibition is stated separately, framed as a violation of the father's domain rather than only the woman's personhood. Reuben's violation (Gen 35:22; 49:3-4) is the paradigmatic case; 1 Cor 5:1 identifies a Corinthian case of this violation as the reason for Paul's most severe church discipline.</p>",
    "9": "<p>You shall not uncover the nakedness of your sister, your father's daughter or your mother's daughter, whether brought up in the family or in another home — the sister prohibition covers full sisters (same father and mother) and half-sisters on either side; the phrase 'brought up in another home' (born outside the household) closes a potential loophole for half-siblings raised separately. Tamar's hope in 2 Sam 13:13 that David might give her to Amnon in marriage suggests that at some point half-sibling marriage was considered possible (or Tamar was desperate); the Levitical prohibition is absolute.</p>",
    "10": "<p>You shall not uncover the nakedness of your son's daughter or of your daughter's daughter, for their nakedness is your own nakedness — grandchild incest is prohibited by derivation: one's grandchild carries one's own flesh (<em>ki ervatekha hennah</em>, their nakedness is your nakedness). The generational extension of kinship ties brings grandchildren under the same protective framework as children.</p>",
    "11": "<p>You shall not uncover the nakedness of your father's wife's daughter, brought up by your father, since she is your sister — stepsister (father's wife's daughter from a previous marriage, not biologically related): prohibited by the family-relationship created by the father-stepmother marriage, even without blood relation. The relational/social kinship created by marriage is treated as equally prohibitive as biological kinship in several of these cases.</p>",
    "12": "<p>You shall not uncover the nakedness of your father's sister; she is your father's near kinswoman — paternal aunt prohibition; the term <em>she'er</em> (flesh-kin, near kinswoman) names the basis for the prohibition. The paternal aunt case appears in the Moses genealogy: Amram married his father's sister Jochebed (Exod 6:20; Num 26:59), a pre-Sinai marriage that the Levitical legislation would prohibit. The law's retrospective inapplicability to Moses's parents is implicit in the Sinai-origin formula of Lev 7:38.</p>",
    "13": "<p>You shall not uncover the nakedness of your mother's sister, for she is your mother's near kinswoman — maternal aunt prohibition; symmetrical with v.12. The two aunt prohibitions (paternal and maternal) create comprehensive coverage of the parents' siblings.</p>",
    "14": "<p>You shall not uncover the nakedness of your father's brother, that is, you shall not approach his wife; she is your aunt — paternal uncle's wife prohibition (not the uncle himself, as the sexual category concerns the man-woman relationships in this framework); the <em>dodah</em> (aunt, uncle's wife) is the prohibited woman, not the uncle's own person. The affinal (by marriage) kinship is treated as prohibitive alongside consanguineal (by blood) kinship.</p>",
    "15": "<p>You shall not uncover the nakedness of your daughter-in-law; she is your son's wife, you shall not uncover her nakedness — daughter-in-law prohibition; the double rationale (she is your daughter-in-law + she is your son's wife) emphasizes both the generational relationship and the specific marital bond. Judah's violation with Tamar (Gen 38:15-18) — even though done in ignorance — is resolved through a complex genealogical providential narrative; the Levitical law makes the prohibition explicit.</p>",
    "16": "<p>You shall not uncover the nakedness of your brother's wife; it is your brother's nakedness — brother's wife prohibition (with the exception of levirate marriage in Deut 25:5-10 for a childless brother). The Herodias case (Mark 6:17-18; Matt 14:3-4) — John the Baptist's rebuke of Herod Antipas for marrying his brother's wife Herodias while the brother (Philip) was still living — represents the precise violation of Lev 18:16, and John's rebuke draws on this legislation.</p>",
    "17": "<p>You shall not uncover the nakedness of a woman and of her daughter, and you shall not take her son's daughter or her daughter's daughter to uncover her nakedness; they are relatives; it is depravity (<em>zimmah hi</em>) — the three-generation prohibition: a woman, her daughter, and her granddaughter may not all be wives of the same man (not simultaneously and not serially). <em>Zimmah</em> (deliberate wickedness, depravity) is the strongest evaluative term in the chapter; this violation receives the burning death penalty in Lev 20:14.</p>",
    "18": "<p>And you shall not take a woman as a rival wife to her sister, uncovering her nakedness while her sister is still alive — the rival-sisters prohibition (not a permanent ban on marrying a deceased wife's sister, but on having two sisters simultaneously as wives): the Jacob/Leah/Rachel case is the obvious background; the legislation formalizes what the narrative already portrayed as a source of profound family dysfunction. The prohibition targets the <em>tzarar</em> (rivalry, vexation) that polygamous sister-marriages create.</p>",
    "19": "<p>You shall not approach a woman to uncover her nakedness while she is in her menstrual uncleanness (<em>niddah</em>) — the niddah prohibition (cf. Lev 15:19-24; 20:18) placed within the sexual prohibition list connects menstrual impurity to the broader <em>ervah</em> framework; sexual intercourse during niddah uncovers the woman's nakedness in her most vulnerable and ritually restricted state.</p>",
    "20": "<p>And you shall not lie sexually with your neighbor's wife and so make yourself unclean with her — adultery (Lev 20:10: capital offense for both parties) is briefly stated in the <em>ervah</em> framework; the <em>tum'ah</em> (impurity) consequence for the man is noted here. The brevity of the adultery prohibition relative to the incest prohibitions reflects that adultery was already comprehensively addressed in the Decalogue (Exod 20:14) and other legislation.</p>",
    "21": "<p>You shall not give any of your children to offer them to Molech, and so profane the name of your God: I am YHWH — Molech sacrifice in a sexual-prohibition chapter is contextually anomalous but theologically coherent: both groups of laws concern misuse of the life-generating capacities of the family; Molech-sacrifice is the ultimate perversion of parental relation (giving children to death rather than life), placed at the center of the chapter's list. Molech was a deity associated with child-sacrifice in Ammon and Canaan (2 Kgs 23:10; Jer 32:35; 1 Kgs 11:7); the practice is attested archaeologically in the topheth sacrificial precinct outside Jerusalem (Gehenna/Ben Hinnom valley).</p>",
    "22": "<p>You shall not lie with a male as with a woman (<em>mishkevei isha</em>); it is an abomination (<em>to'evah</em>) — <em>to'evah</em> (abomination, something YHWH detests) is applied to several violations in Lev 18 and 20 (vv.26,29,30; 20:13); it is not a unique categorical term applied only to this prohibition but a severity marker applied to violations that fall outside YHWH's created order. The <em>mishkevei isha</em> (lyings of a woman) formula specifies the sexual category being prohibited by reference to its female analog.</p>",
    "23": "<p>And you shall not lie with any animal and so make yourself unclean with it, neither shall any woman give herself to an animal to lie with it: it is perversion (<em>tevel</em>) — bestiality (Lev 20:15-16: capital for both man and woman) is the closing prohibition of the sexual list; <em>tevel</em> (confusion, mixing of kinds, violation of species boundaries) is the evaluative term, the same used in Lev 19:19 for hybrid-kind violations (crossbreeding, mixed seed, mixed fabric). The common thread: violations of created categories are tevel; violations of YHWH's sanctity are to'evah.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Do not make yourselves unclean by any of these things, for by all these the nations I am driving out before you have made themselves unclean — the closing frame (vv.24-30) returns to the Egypt/Canaan contrast of vv.1-5; the Canaanite nations' defilement through these practices is the reason YHWH is expelling them. The sexual violations are not merely interpersonal wrongs but land-defiling acts with territorial consequences.</p>",
    "25": "<p>And the land became unclean, so that I punished its iniquity upon it, and the land vomited out its inhabitants (<em>vataqe ha-aretz et-yoshveiha</em>) — the land-vomiting metaphor: the land has a quasi-organic response to moral pollution; it cannot contain the accumulated defilement and expels its population as a contaminated stomach expels its contents. This is one of the most theologically distinctive concepts in the Holiness Code; the land is not inert but responsive to the moral quality of its inhabitants' behavior.</p>",
    "26": "<p>But you shall keep my statutes and my rules and do none of these abominations, either the native or the stranger who sojourns among you — the covenant counter-command: Israel and its sojourners are to follow YHWH's laws, not the Canaanite practices. The inclusion of the sojourner (<em>ger</em>) in both prohibition and command confirms that the land's holiness requirement applies to all who inhabit it, not only to covenant-Israel.</p>",
    "27": "<p>For the people of the land, who were before you, did all of these abominations, so that the land became unclean — the historical basis for the legislation: the Canaanites' sexual violations produced the land's defilement that now requires their expulsion. Israel is being brought into a land that has already been through one cycle of defilement-and-expulsion; the warning is experientially grounded in the history of the land itself.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Lest the land vomit you out when you make it unclean, as it vomited out the nation that was before you — the direct warning: the same land-vomiting that expelled the Canaanites will expel Israel if they commit the same violations. The symmetry between Canaan's fate and Israel's potential fate is the chapter's most urgent ethical logic; Israel's election does not exempt them from the land's moral ecology. The prophets later invoke this warning as the theological explanation for the Babylonian exile (Ezek 36:17; Amos 2:9-10).</p>",
    "29": "<p>For everyone who does any of these abominations, the persons who do them shall be cut off from among their people — the comprehensive karet threat for all the prohibitions listed in vv.6-23; the individual penalties specified in Lev 20 (capital vs. karet) refine this general statement, but the basic principle is that any of these violations removes the offender from the covenant community.</p>",
    "30": "<p>So keep my charge never to practice any of these abominable customs that were practiced before you, and never to make yourselves unclean by them: I am YHWH your God — the final divine self-identification formula closes the entire chapter with the same formula that opened it (v.2). The bracketing <em>ani YHWH Eloheichem</em> encapsulates the chapter's theological argument: all sexual ethics flows from and returns to the covenant identity. The charge to 'keep my charge' (<em>ushmartem et-mishmarti</em>) is the same expression used for the priestly duty (Num 3:28) and for the general covenant obligation (Gen 26:5; Lev 22:9).</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    e = load_comm('mkt-context', 'leviticus')
    merge_comm(e, DATA)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'leviticus', e)
    print('Leviticus 16-18 mkt-context written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
